[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Weaviate *(we-vee-eight)* is an open-source, AI vector database.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Use this documentation to get started with Weaviate and learn how to get the most out of Weaviate's features.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Start with the Quickstart tutorial – an end-to-end demo that takes 15–30 minutes.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Check out Weaviate Academy – a learning platform centered around AI-native development.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] The Weaviate documentation is structured into multiple units based on the service and functionality.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Enable and configure the Weaviate MCP server so LLMs and IDE assistants can interact with your Weaviate instance.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Avoid hallucinations and improve your AI-assisted coding experience.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Weaviate is an **open-source vector database** designed to store and index both data objects and their vector embeddings.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] This architecture enables advanced semantic search capabilities by comparing the meaning encoded in vectors rather than relying solely on keyword matching.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Become familiar with Weaviate's architecture, core concepts, and key capabilities.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Understand how its features and integrations map to AI builders' needs.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] The Weaviate ecosystem consists of multiple tools and services centered around building cloud-native AI-powered applications.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Get help, share what you're building, and connect with the Weaviate community and team.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Ask technical questions, get help with your cluster, and connect with other developers and the Weaviate team.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Open to everyone and a great place to start.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] The Support page explains all the ways to get help from the Weaviate team.
[src:weaviate/developers-weaviate] Give us a star on GitHub to support our work.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] The algorithm is commonly used for searching vector data.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] In these systems, an item such as a document, image, song, or user profile is represented by a list of numbers called a vector.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Items with similar vectors are treated as similar according to the model that produced the vectors.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] HNSW provides a way to search these vectors quickly, especially in large datasets.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Each vector is a node, and links connect it to some nearby vectors.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] The graph has several layers: upper layers contain fewer nodes and act like a rough map, while the bottom layer contains all nodes and gives a more detailed view.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] A search starts in an upper layer, follows links toward nodes that are closer to the query, and then repeats the process in lower layers until it finds a set of likely nearest neighbors.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] The nearest neighbor search problem asks which items in a dataset are closest to a query item.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] A direct search can compare the query with every item in the dataset, but this becomes slow when the dataset is large.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Exact search methods based on spatial trees, such as the k-d tree and R-tree, can also become less effective for high-dimensional data, a problem often associated with the curse of dimensionality.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Approximate nearest neighbor methods trade some exactness for speed or lower resource use.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Instead of always guaranteeing the exact closest item, they try to return close items quickly.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Other approximate methods include locality-sensitive hashing and product quantization.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] HNSW builds on research into small-world networks and navigable graphs.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] In a small-world graph, most nodes can be reached from other nodes through a short chain of links.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] In a navigable graph, a search procedure can use local information to move toward a target.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Jon Kleinberg's work on navigation in small-world networks is an important example of this research area.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Later work studied ways to add links that make graphs easier to navigate greedily.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] The HNSW algorithm extends earlier navigable small world methods for similarity search by adding a hierarchy of graph layers.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] This hierarchy helps the algorithm find a good region of the graph before doing a more detailed search in the bottom layer.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] In this graph, nearby vectors are connected by edges.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] The algorithm uses these edges to move through the dataset, rather than scanning every vector.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Every vector appears in the bottom layer.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Some vectors are also placed in higher layers, with fewer vectors appearing as the layers go upward.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] The upper layers allow long-range movement across the dataset, while the lower layers allow a more detailed search near promising candidates.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] At each step, the algorithm looks at neighboring nodes and moves to a neighbor that is closer to the query.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] When it cannot find a closer neighbor in that layer, it moves down to the next layer.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] In the bottom layer, it explores a wider set of candidate nodes and returns the nearest candidates found.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] This search strategy is often described as greedy navigation.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] The algorithm repeatedly chooses locally better nodes, using the graph structure to approach the query point.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] When a new vector is inserted, the algorithm assigns it a maximum layer, searches for nearby existing nodes, and connects the new node to selected neighbors in each layer where it appears.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Implementations usually expose parameters that control the trade-off between speed, accuracy, memory use, and construction time.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] A higher number of graph connections can improve recall but requires more memory.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] A larger search candidate list can improve accuracy but makes queries slower.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] A larger construction candidate list can improve the quality of the graph but makes index building slower.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Because HNSW is approximate, its results are not always identical to a full exact search.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Its practical performance depends on the dataset, distance measure, implementation, and parameter settings.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Benchmarking studies have found HNSW-based libraries to be strong performers among approximate nearest neighbor methods, although worst-case performance can differ from performance on common benchmark datasets.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] HNSW is used as an index in systems that store and search high-dimensional vectors.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] These systems include vector databases, search engines, and database extensions.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Typical uses include semantic search, recommender systems, image similarity search, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Several software projects implement or support HNSW.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Libraries include hnswlib, which is associated with the original HNSW authors, and FAISS.
[src:weaviate/hierarchical-navigable-small-world] Database and search systems that document HNSW support include Apache Lucene, Chroma, ClickHouse, DuckDB, MariaDB, Milvus, pgvector, Qdrant, and Redis.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Weaviate supports two approaches to store vectors: automatic vectorization at import using integrated models (OpenAI, Cohere, HuggingFace, and others) or direct import of pre-computed vector embeddings.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Production deployments benefit from built-in multi-tenancy, replication, RBAC authorization, and many other features.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] See the installation docs for more deployment options, such as AWS and GCP.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] You can easily start Weaviate and a local vector embedding model with Docker.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] This example uses the `Model2Vec` vectorizer, but you can choose any other embedding model provider or bring your own pre-generated vectors.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] There are also additional community-maintained libraries.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Weaviate exposes REST API, gRPC API, and GraphQL API to communicate with the database server.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] For a complete list of all functionalities, visit the official Weaviate documentation.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Weaviate Agent Skills is a collection of skills for AI coding agents (Claude Code, Cursor, GitHub Copilot, and others) that enable them to work with Weaviate more accurately and efficiently.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Skills cover searching, querying, collection management, data import, and full application blueprints (RAG, agentic RAG, chatbots, and more).
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] These demos are working applications that highlight some of Weaviate's capabilities.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Their source code is available on GitHub.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] We welcome and appreciate contributions!
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Please see our Contributor guide for the development setup, code style guidelines, testing requirements and the pull request process.
[src:weaviate/main-readme-md] Join our Community forum to discuss ideas and get help.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:weaviate/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] A **vector database**, **vector store** or **vector search engine** is a database that stores and retrieves embeddings of data in vector space.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Vector databases typically implement approximate nearest neighbor algorithms so users can search for records semantically similar to a given input, unlike traditional databases which primarily look up records by exact match.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Use-cases for vector databases include similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Vector embeddings are mathematical representations of data in a high-dimensional space.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] In this space, each dimension corresponds to a feature of the data, with the number of dimensions ranging from a few hundred to tens of thousands, depending on the complexity of the data being represented.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Each data item is represented by one vector in this space.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Words, phrases, or entire documents, as well as images, audio, and other types of data, can all be vectorized.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] These feature vectors may be computed from the raw data using machine learning methods such as feature extraction algorithms, word embeddings or deep learning networks.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] The goal is that semantically similar data items receive feature vectors close to each other.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Vector retrieval can be combined with metadata filtering or lexical search to support filtered and hybrid retrieval workflows.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] These techniques may also be combined in vector search systems.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] In recent benchmarks, HNSW-based implementations have been among the best performers.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Conferences such as the International Conference on Similarity Search and Applications (SISAP) and the Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) have hosted competitions on vector search in large databases.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Vector databases are used in a wide range of machine learning applications including similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] An especially common use-case for vector databases is in retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), a method to improve domain-specific responses of large language models.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] The retrieval component of a RAG can be any search system, but is most often implemented as a vector database.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Text documents describing the domain of interest are collected, and for each document or document section, a feature vector (known as an "embedding") is computed, typically using a deep learning network, and stored in a vector database along with a link to the document.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] Given a user prompt, the feature vector of the prompt is computed, and the database is queried to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:weaviate/vector-database] These are then automatically added into the context window of the large language model, and the large language model proceeds to create a response to the prompt given this context.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It's a key component of vector databases that helps to significantly **increase the speed** of the search process of similarity search with only a minimal tradeoff in search accuracy (HNSW index), or efficiently store many subsets of data in a small memory footprint (flat index).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The dynamic index can even start off as a flat index and then dynamically switch to the HNSW index as it scales past a threshold.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Weaviate's vector-first storage system takes care of all storage operations with a vector index.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Storing data in a vector-first manner not only allows for semantic or context-based search, but also makes it possible to store *very* large amounts of data without decreasing performance (assuming scaled well horizontally or having sufficient shards for the indexes).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This page explains what vector indexes are, and what purpose they serve in the Weaviate vector database.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] In vector databases, a vector index is a data structure that organizes vector embeddings to enable efficient similarity search.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Indexing vector databases properly is crucial for performance, and different index types serve different purposes - from the simple flat index to more sophisticated approaches like HNSW and HFresh.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Vector embeddings are a great way to represent meaning.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Understanding how to index a vector is crucial for working with vector databases effectively.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Vectors embeddings are arrays of elements that can capture meaning from different data types, such as texts, images, videos, and other content.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The number of elements are called dimensions.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] High dimension vectors capture more information, but they are harder to work with.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Vector databases make it easier to work with high dimensional vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Consider search; Vector databases efficiently measure semantic similarity between data objects.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When you run a similarity search, a vector database like Weaviate uses a vectorized version of the query to find objects in the database that have vectors similar to the query vector.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Vectors are like coordinates in a multi-dimensional space.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] A very simple vector might represent objects, *words* in this case, in a 2-dimensional space.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] In the graph below, the words `Apple` and `Banana` are shown close to each other.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] `Newspaper` and `Magazine` are also close to each other, but they are far away from `Apple` and `Banana` in the same vector space.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Within each pair, the distance between words is small because the objects have similar vector embeddings.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The distance between the pairs is larger because the difference between the vectors is larger.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Intuitively, fruits are similar to each other, but fruits are not similar to reading material.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] For more details of this representation, see: (GloVe) and vector embeddings.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Another way to think of this is how products are placed in a supermarket.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] You'd expect to find `Apples` close to `Bananas`, because they are both fruit.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] But when you are searching for a `Magazine`, you would move away from the `Apples` and `Bananas`, more towards the aisle with, for example, `Newspapers`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This is how the semantics of concepts can be stored in Weaviate as well, depending on the module you're using to calculate the numbers in the vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Not only words or text can be indexed as vectors, but also images, video, DNA sequences, etc.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Read more about which model to use here.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] You might be also interested in our blog post Vector search explained.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Let's explore how to index a vector using different approaches supported by Weaviate.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Many different types of vector indexes exist.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] A majority of them are designed to speed up searches by reducing the number of vectors that need to be compared.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] However, they do this in different ways, and each has its own strengths and weaknesses.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Graph indexes form a network of vectors, such that similar vectors are connected to each other.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This allows for fast "traversal" of the graph to find similar vectors to a query vector.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] HNSW, or "Hierarchical Navigable Small World", is the most common graph index type.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It creates a set of "layers" of vectors, to enable fast traversal of the graph.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] They are very scalable, allow incremental updates, and efficient for high-dimensional vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This is the default index type in Weaviate.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Tree-based indexes divide the vectors into a tree structure.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] ANNOY, or "Approximate Nearest Neighbors Oh Yeah", is a well-known tree-based index.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It divides the vectors into a binary tree structure.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] They can be memory-efficient, and are good for low-dimensional vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] However, it may be costly to update the index over time, as the tree may need to be rebuilt.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Cluster-based indexes group vectors based on their similarity.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] As a result, the search space is reduced to only the cluster(s) that is most likely to contain the nearest neighbors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Their search accuracy (recall and precision) may generally be lower than graph-based indexes, but they can be more memory-efficient.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] A flat index is the simplest type of index.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It stores all vectors in a single list, and searches through all of them to find the nearest neighbors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This is extremely memory-efficient, but does not scale well, as the search time grows linearly with the number of vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Weaviate's `hnsw` index is a custom implementation of the Hierarchical Navigable Small World (HNSW) algorithm that offers full CRUD-support.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] At build time, the HNSW algorithm creates a series of layers.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] At query time, the HNSW algorithm uses the layers to build a list of approximate nearest neighbors (ANN) quickly and efficiently.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Consider this diagram of a vector index using HNSW.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] An individual object can exist in more than one layer, but every object in the database is represented in the lowest layer (layer zero in the picture).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The layer zero data objects are very well connected to each other.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Each layer above the lowest layer has fewer data object, and fewer connections.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The data objects in the higher layers correspond to the objects in the lower layers, but each higher layer has exponentially fewer objects than the layer below.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The HNSW algorithm takes advantage of the layers to efficiently process large amounts of data.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When a search query comes in, the HNSW algorithm finds the closest matching data points in the highest layer.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Then, HNSW goes one layer deeper, and finds the closest data points in that layer to the ones in the higher layer.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The algorithm searches the lower layer to create a new list of nearest neighbors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Then, HNSW uses the new list and repeats the process on the next layer down.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When it gets to the deepest layer, the HNSW algorithm returns the data objects closest to the search query.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Since there are relatively few data objects on the higher layers, HNSW has to search fewer objects.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This means HNSW 'jumps' over large amounts of data that it doesn't need to search.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When a data store has only one layer, the search algorithm can't skip unrelated objects.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It has to search significantly more data objects even though they are unlikely to match.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] HNSW is an in-memory index, where each node in the graph as well as each edge between nodes are stored in memory.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This means that the size of the index in memory is directly proportional to the number of vectors in the index, as well as the number of connections between vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] As you can see, the memory requirements of an HNSW index can quickly become a bottleneck.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This is where quantization can be used to reduce the size of the index in memory.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Alternatively, the disk-based HFresh index keeps only a compressed centroid index in memory, which can dramatically reduce the memory footprint.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] HNSW is very fast, memory efficient, approach to similarity search.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The memory cache only stores the highest layer instead of storing all of the data objects in the lowest layer.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When the search moves from a higher layer to a lower one, HNSW only adds the data objects that are closest to the search query.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This means HNSW uses a relatively small amount of memory compared to other search algorithms.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Have another look at the diagram; it demonstrates how the HNSW algorithm searches.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The search vector in the top layer connects to a partial result in layer one.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The objects in layer one lead HNSW to the result set in layer zero.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This allows HNSW to skip objects that are unrelated to the search query.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Inserting a vector into an HNSW index works in a similar way.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The HNSW algorithm finds the closest data objects in the highest layer, and then moves down to the next layer.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It continues until it finds the best place to insert the new vector.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The HNSW algorithm then connects the new vector to the existing vectors in that layer.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] HNSW parameters can be adjusted to adjust search quality against speed.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The `ef` parameter is a critical setting for balancing the trade-off between search speed and quality.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The `ef` parameter dictates the size of the dynamic list used by the HNSW algorithm during the search process.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] A higher `ef` value results in a more extensive search, enhancing accuracy but potentially slowing down the query.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] In contrast, a lower `ef` makes the search faster but might compromise on accuracy.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This balance is crucial in scenarios where either speed or accuracy is a priority.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] For instance, in applications where rapid responses are critical, a lower `ef` might be preferable, even at the expense of some accuracy.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Conversely, in analytical or research contexts where precision is paramount, a higher `ef` would be more suitable, despite the increased query time.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] `ef` can be configured explicitly or dynamically.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This feature is particularly beneficial in environments with varying query patterns.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When `ef` is configured dynamically, Weaviate optimizes the balance between speed and recall based on real-time query requirements.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Weaviate adjusts the size of the ANN list based on the query response limit.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The calculation also takes into account the values of `dynamicEfMin`, `dynamicEfMax`, and `dynamicEfFactor`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The `ef` parameter controls the size of the ANN list at query time.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] You can configure a specific list size or else let Weaviate configure the list dynamically.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] If you choose dynamic `ef`, Weaviate provides several options to control the size of the ANN list.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The length of the list is determined by the query response limit that you set in your query.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Weaviate uses the query limit as an anchor and modifies the size of ANN list according to the values you set for the `dynamicEf` parameters.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The dynamic list size will be set as the query limit multiplied by `dynamicEfFactor`, modified by a minimum of `dynamicEfMin` and a maximum of `dynamicEfMax`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To keep search recall high, the actual dynamic `ef` value stays above `dynamicEfMin` even if the query limit is small enough to suggest a lower value.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To keep search speed reasonable even when retrieving large result sets, the dynamic `ef` value is limited to `dynamicEfMax`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Weaviate doesn't exceed `dynamicEfMax` even if the query limit is large enough to suggest a higher value.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] If the query limit is higher than `dynamicEfMax`, `dynamicEfMax` does not have any effect.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] In this case, dynamic `ef` value is equal to the query limit.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To determine the length of the ANN list, Weaviate multiples the query limit by `dynamicEfFactor`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The list range is modified by `dynamicEfMin` and `dynamicEfMax`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Consider this GraphQL query that sets a limit of 4.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Imagine the collection has dynamic `ef` configured.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The resulting search list has these characteristics.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] If you use the `docker-compose.yml` file from Weaviate to run your local instance, the `QUERY_DEFAULTS_LIMIT` environment variable sets a reasonable default query limit.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To prevent out of memory errors,`QUERY_DEFAULTS_LIMIT` is significantly lower than `QUERY_MAXIMUM_RESULTS`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To change the default limit, edit the value for `QUERY_DEFAULTS_LIMIT` when you configure your Weaviate instance.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Cleanup is an async process runs that rebuilds the HNSW graph after deletes and updates.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Prior to cleanup, objects are marked as deleted, but they are still connected to the HNSW graph.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] During cleanup, the edges are reassigned and the objects are deleted for good.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The **flat index** is one of the fundamental ways to implement vector indexing in databases.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] As the name suggests, it's a simple, lightweight index that is fast to build and has a very small memory footprint.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This index type is a good choice for use cases where each end user (i.e. tenant) has their own, isolated, dataset, such as in a SaaS product for example, or a database of isolated record sets.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] As the name suggests, the flat index is a single layer of disk-backed data objects and thus a very small memory footprint.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The flat index is a good choice for small collections, such as for multi-tenancy use cases.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] A drawback of the flat index is that it does not scale well to large collections as it has a linear time complexity as a function of the number of data objects, unlike the `hnsw` index which has a logarithmic time complexity.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Dynamic indexes require asynchronous indexing.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To enable asynchronous indexing in a self-hosted Weaviate instance, set the `ASYNC_INDEXING` environment variable to `true`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] If your instance is hosted in Weaviate Cloud, use the Weaviate Cloud console to enable asynchronous indexing.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The flat index is ideal for use cases with a small object count and provides lower memory overhead and good latency.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] As the object count increases the HNSW index provides a more viable solution as HNSW speeds up search.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The goal of the dynamic index is to shorten latencies during querying time at the cost of a larger memory footprint as you scale.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When memory is your main constraint, the HFresh index is another option: it avoids keeping the full index in memory, trading some query speed for much lower memory use.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] By configuring a dynamic index, you can automatically switch from flat to HNSW indexes.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This switch occurs when the object count exceeds a specified threshold (by default 10,000).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This functionality only works with async indexing enabled.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When the threshold is hit while importing, all the data piles up in the async queue, the HNSW index is constructed in the background and when ready the swap from flat to HNSW is completed.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Currently, this is only a one-way upgrade from a flat to an HNSW index, it does not support changing back to a flat index even if the object count goes below the threshold due to deletion.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This is particularly useful in a multi-tenant setup where building an HNSW index per tenant would introduce extra overhead.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] With a dynamic index, as individual tenants grow their index will switch from flat to HNSW, while smaller tenants' indexes remain flat.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The **HFresh index** is a cluster-based vector index that uses HNSW for the centroid index.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It is based on the SPFresh algorithm, which organizes vectors into posting lists (clusters) for efficient retrieval.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Read more about SPFresh in SPFresh: Incremental In-Place Update for Billion-Scale Vector Search.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] **Using an HNSW index** to efficiently search the centroids.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] **Searching only the most relevant posting lists** (clusters) for a query.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This approach can provide memory efficiency benefits for large datasets while maintaining good search performance.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The key trade-off is between memory usage and search recall, controlled by parameters like `searchProbe` (number of posting lists to search) and `replicas` (number of posting lists each vector is added to).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Only the centroid index stays in memory, compressed with 8-bit rotational quantization (RQ).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The posting lists are stored on disk, compressed with 1-bit RQ.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] A query searches the in-memory centroid index to pick a few relevant postings, reads only those postings from disk, and rescores the top candidates against the uncompressed vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Because only a small subset of the data is read per query, disk I/O stays bounded and latency stays predictable as the dataset grows.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] HFresh also rebalances its posting lists in the background as data changes, so it does not require periodic full index rebuilds.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] HFresh is not designed to beat HNSW on raw query throughput.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] It targets deployments where memory efficiency matters more than peak QPS, and where the application can tolerate slightly higher query latencies.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] HFresh only supports `cosine` and `l2-squared` distance metrics.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] For configuration details, see the HFresh index parameters.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] For optimal search and import performance, previously imported vectors need to be in memory.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] A disk lookup for a vector is orders of magnitudes slower than memory lookup, so the disk cache should be used sparingly.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] However, Weaviate can limit the number of vectors in memory.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] By default, this limit is set to one trillion (`1e12`) objects when a new collection is created.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] During import set `vectorCacheMaxObjects` high enough that all vectors can be held in memory.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Import performance drops drastically when there isn't enough memory to hold all of the vectors in the cache.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] After import, when your workload is mostly querying, experiment with vector cache limits that are less than your total dataset size.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Vectors that aren't currently in cache are added to the cache if there is still room.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] If the cache fills, Weaviate drops the whole cache.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] All future vectors have to be read from disk for the first time.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Then, subsequent queries run against the cache until it fills again and the procedure repeats.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Note that the cache can be a very valuable tool if you have a large dataset, and a large percentage of users only query a specific subset of vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] In this case you might be able to serve the largest user group from cache while requiring disk lookups for "irregular" queries.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This feature relates to the vector index, specifically only to the HNSW and HFresh indexes.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] With synchronous indexing, the vector index is updated in lockstep with the object store.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Updating an HNSW index can be an expensive operation, especially as the size of the index grows.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] As a result, the indexing operation can be the bottleneck in the system, slowing down the time for user requests to be completed.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When asynchronous indexing is enabled, all vector indexing operations go through a queue.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This applies to not only batch imports, but also to single object imports, deletions, and updates.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This means that the object store can be updated quickly to finish performing user requests while the vector index updates in the background.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Asynchronous indexing is especially useful for importing large amounts of data.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This means that there will be a short delay between object creation and the object being available for vector search using the HNSW index.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The number of objects in the queue can be monitored per node as shown here.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] In Weaviate `v1.22` to `v1.27`, the async indexing feature only affected batch import operations, using an in-memory queue.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Starting in `v1.28`, the async indexing feature has been expanded to include single object imports, deletions, and updates.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Additionally, the in-memory queue has been replaced with a persistent, on-disk queue.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This change allows for more robust handling of indexing operations, and improves performance though reduction of lock contention and memory usage.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The use of an on-disk queue may result in a slight increase in disk usage, however this is expected to be a small percentage of the total disk usage.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Yes, you can read more about it in vector quantization (compression).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Note that the vector index type parameter only specifies how the vectors of data objects are *indexed*.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The index is used for data retrieval and similarity search.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The `vectorizer` parameter determines how the data vectors are created (which numbers the vectors contain).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] `vectorizer` specifies a module, such as `text2vec-contextionary`, that Weaviate uses to create the vectors.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] (You can also set to `vectorizer` to `none` if you want to import your own vectors).
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To learn more about configuring the collection, see this how-to page.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] All of the distance metrics, such as cosine similarity, can be used with most vector index types.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The HFresh index only supports `cosine` and `l2-squared` distance metrics.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The index type can be specified per data collection via the collection definition settings, according to available vector index settings.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] There are situations where it doesn't make sense to vectorize a collection.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] For example, if the collection consists solely of references between two other collections, or if the collection contains mostly duplicate elements.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Importing duplicate vectors into HNSW is very expensive.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The import algorithm checks early on if a candidate vector's distance is greater than the worst candidate's distance.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] When there are lots of duplicate vectors, this early exit condition is never met so each import or query results in an exhaustive search.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] To avoid indexing a collection, set `"skip"` to `"true"`.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] There are different ANN algorithms, you can find a nice overview of them on this website.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] The ANN benchmark page contains a wide variety of vector search use cases and relative benchmarks.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] This page is ideal for finding a dataset similar to yours and learning what the most optimal settings are.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Ask questions and connect with other developers on our Community forum.
[src:weaviate/vector-index] Find the right channel on the Support page.
[src:weaviate/weaviate-concepts] The **Concepts** section explains various aspects related to Weaviate and its architecture to help you get the most out of it.
[src:weaviate/weaviate-concepts] You can read these sections in any order.
[src:weaviate/weaviate-concepts] If you are after a practical guide with code examples, check out the quickstart tutorial.
